                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-306-victim2215 t18310908-306-viclabel1575"></join>, who lives in <placeName id="t18310908-306-crimeloc1576">Cromer-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310908-306-crimeloc1576" type="placeName" value="Cromer-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310908-306-crimeloc1576" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-306-off1573 t18310908-306-crimeloc1576"></join>. On the 11th of March the prisoner took a room at our house, and on the 5th of September I took an officer, and examined the room; I then missed this property - the duplicates were produced.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q.Is your husband here? A. Yes; I was greatly surprised at the loss of these things - she had pawned before, but the things were replaced, and it was made up; she had not apprised me of pawning these things - they owed money for rent, but since she had been in prison, her husband had paid 1l. 13s.; the prisoner had said she had 2000l. coming to her, I do not consider such a person could be in distress: I had not asked them for rent - she had promised to pay the rent two or three days before she was taken.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-306-person2218">
                  WILLIAM 
                  HALL
               <interp inst="t18310908-306-person2218" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-306-person2218" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-306-person2218" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-constable. I took the prisoner on the 5th of September; I asked if she had any duplicates - she said Yes, went to a drawer, and pulled out a purse with a great many duplicates; I looked them over and the prosecutor claimed some of them - the prisoner said her husband was in the City, she thought he would not he long, but if he were there, he would know nothing about it; as she had pawned them herself - she said the pillow-cases had been lost at the wash; she made no difficulty of showing the duplicates.</p>

               <p>Cross-examined. Q.Were they not in distress? A. They did not appear so; there was a good dinner providing, of meat and pudding - there were some duplicates for pledges as low as 6d.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-306-person2219">
                  THOMAS 
                  WARD
               <interp inst="t18310908-306-person2219" type="surname" value="WARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-306-person2219" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-306-person2219" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the employ of Mr. Burgess, a pawnbroker. I have two sheets, pawned on the 31st of March, and on the 31st of August, by a woman; I cannot say who - I gave her these duplicates.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-306-person2220">
                  ELIZABETH 
                  BARTLETT
               <interp inst="t18310908-306-person2220" type="surname" value="BARTLETT"></interp>
